{"title_page": "Azam Tariq (religious leader)", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n| name          = Azam Tariq\n| image         =\n| caption       =\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|1962|07|10}}\n| birth_place         =[[Chichawatni]], [[Punjab]], [[Pakistan]]\n| death_date          = {{Death date and age|2003|10|06|1962|07|10}}\n| death_place  = near Islamabad\n| placeofburial_label = \n| children     = [[Moavia Azam Tariq]]\n| placeofburial_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n| allegiance    = [[Sipah-e-Sahaba Pakistan]] \n| branch        =\n| serviceyears  = \n| rank          = \n| unit          =\n| commands      =\n| battles       =\n| awards        =\n| relations     =\n| laterwork     =\n}}\n\n'''Azam Tariq ''' ([[Urdu]]: '''\u0627\u0639\u0638\u0645 \u0637\u0627\u0631\u0642''' March 1962 \u2013 6 October 2003) was the leader of the politico-religious organisation [[ Sipah-e-Sahaba Pakistan]], a [[Deobandi]]  organization, which was officially banned by the government of [[Pakistan]] in August 2001.On 26 June 2018, Pakistan lifted ban on Sipah-e-Sahaba Pakistan.[https://tribune.com.pk/story/1744294/1-govt-lifts-ban-aswj-unfreezes-assets-chief-ahmed-ludhianvi/]\n\nAfter his death in 2003, [[Muhammad Ahmed Ludhianvi]] was selected as the president of [[Sipah-e-Sahaba Pakistan]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nHe was born to a poor farmer Mohammad Fateh in [[Chichawatni]].<ref name=\"newslinemagazine.com\">http://newslinemagazine.com/magazine/in-death-as-in-life/</ref> He studied at a local madrassa and then enrolled in the Jamia Uloom Islamia in Binori Town, Karachi.<ref name=\"newslinemagazine.com\"/> [[Maulana Moawiyah Azam]] is his elder son, currently active somewhere.\n\n==Career==\nAzam Tariq was elected three times to the [[National Assembly of Pakistan]] in [[Jhang]].<ref>https://www.middle-east-online.com/en/pakistan\u2019s-sunni-shia-rift</ref>\n\nIn August 2001, Pakistani president [[Pervez Musharraf]] banned seven alleged Islamic organizations, including Sipah-e-Sahaba, and Azam Tariq was arrested and jailed on charges of terrorism.\n\n==Assassination==\nAzam Tariq was shot and killed in an attack on October 6, 2003 in a hail of bullets alongside [[Islamabad]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://archive.democrats.com/preview.cfm?term=Pakistan | title = The Hammer Poised to Strike in Pakistan | date = Oct 10, 2003 | website = archive.democrats.com | archive-url = https://archive.today/20051127085005/http://archive.democrats.com/preview.cfm?term=Pakistan | archive-date = November 27, 2005 | url-status = live | access-date = May 8, 2019 }}</ref> as he left the [[M2 motorway (Pakistan)|M2 Motorway]] to enter the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/118945 |title=Azam Tariq gunned down in Islamabad |date=7 October 2003 |access-date=29 June 2018 |website=Dawn.com}}</ref> \n\nThe assassination come after a growing wave of violent incidents in Pakistan between the sectarian Sunni dominance and the smaller community of the Shiah Muslims. Violence peaked up in July with the [[2003 Quetta mosque bombing]] and the massacre of more than 50 people.<ref>{{cite web | author = [[Imtiaz Gul]] | url = https://www.aljazeera.com/archive/2003/10/20084916332362185.html | title = Cleric murder highlights sectarianism | date = Oct 8, 2003 | publisher = [[Aljazeera.com]] | archive-url = https://archive.today/20170424101307/https://www.aljazeera.com/archive/2003/10/20084916332362185.html | archive-date = April 24, 2017 | url-status = live | access-date = May 8, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nOn May 11, 2017, the [[Federal Investigation Agency]] (FIA) arrested a proclaimed offender after 13 years who murdered him.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/1406951/suspect-azam-tariqs-murder-arrested-islamabad-airport/|title=Former ASWJ leader Maulana Azam Tariq's suspected murderer arrested from Islamabad airport |publisher=The Express Tribune |date=11 May 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n===Books by him===\n*''R\u016bd\u0101d-i \u02bbishq o vaf\u0101'', Jhang : Markaz\u012b Daftar-i Sip\u0101h-i \u1e62a\u1e25\u0101bah, 1999-2004, around 1000 pages (in 2 volumes). <small>Author's memoirs.</small>\n*''Ahamm\u012byat-i \u1e25ad\u012bs\u0332 dar d\u012bn'', K\u0101bul : Mayvand ; Peshawar : Kit\u0101bkh\u0101nah-\u02bci Sab\u0101, 2005, 298 p. <small>Importance of [[Hadith]] for Islam, in Persian.</small>\n*''K\u0332h\u0332ut\u0324b\u0101t-i jarnail, al-ma\u02bbr\u016bf, K\u0332h\u0332ut\u0324b\u0101t-i jel'', Jhang : Markaz\u012b Daftar-i Sip\u0101h-i \u1e62a\u1e25\u0101bah, 2001. <small>Collection of speeches written in jail (1998-1999) collected by Ab\u016b Us\u0101mah Z\u0324iy\u0101urra\u1e25m\u0101n N\u0101\u1e63ir.</small>\n\n===Books about him===\n*Mu\u1e25ammad Nad\u012bm Q\u0101sim\u012b, ''\u1e24ay\u0101t-i A\u02bb\u1e93am T\u0324\u0101riq : Mu\u1e25ammad A\u02bb\u1e93am T\u0324\u0101riq ke mufa\u1e63\u1e63il \u1e25\u0101l\u0101t-i zindag\u012b'', Fai\u1e63al\u0101b\u0101d : Ish\u0101\u02bbatulma\u02bb\u0101rif, 1998, 413 p.\n*Mu\u1e25ammad Nad\u012bm Mu\u02bb\u0101viyah, ''P\u0101rl\u012bman\u1e6d k\u0101 shahz\u0101dah : S\u0332\u0101n\u012b-i jarnail-i Sip\u0101h-yi \u1e62a\u1e25\u0101bah ... \u1e24az\u0324rat Maul\u0101n\u0101 Mu\u1e25ammad A\u02bb\u1e93am T\u0324\u0101riq shah\u012bd ke mufa\u1e63\u1e63al \u1e25\u0101l\u0101t-i zindag\u012b aur P\u0101rl\u012bmant k\u012b taq\u0101r\u012br'' Kar\u0101ch\u012b : Maktabah-yi K\u0332h\u0332il\u0101fat-i R\u0101shidah, 2005, 376 p.\n==See also==\n* [[Haq Nawaz Jhangvi]] \n* [[Isar-ul-Haq Qasmi]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.shianews.com/hi/articles/politics/0000116.php Shia News]: a partisan account of Azam Tariq's release in 2001, with a background of the history of Sunni-Shia violence in Pakistan\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070927185726/http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=story_21-3-2004_pg7_28 Pakistan ''Daily Times'' October 7, 2004]\n* [http://www.shianews.com/hi/talking_corner/topic_id/0000015.php Shia News report of Azam Tariq's assassination]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060206231705/http://www.newsline.com.pk/NewsOct2003/stopoct1.htm An Eye for an Eye?] Azam Tariq's assassination news by Newsline (Pakistan).\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tariq, Azam}}\n\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:2003 deaths]]\n[[Category:Pakistani prisoners and detainees]]\n[[Category:Pakistani religious leaders]]\n[[Category:Pakistani MNAs 1990\u20131993]]\n[[Category:Pakistani MNAs 1993\u20131996]]\n[[Category:Pakistani MNAs 2002\u20132007]]\n[[Category:People from Chichawatni]]\n[[Category:Shia\u2013Sunni sectarian violence in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Assassinated Pakistani people]]\n[[Category:Assassinated religious leaders]]\n[[Category:Pakistani far-right politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n| name          = Azam Tariq\n| image         =\n| caption       =\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|1962|07|10}}\n| birth_place         =[[Chichawatni]], [[Punjab]], [[Pakistan]]\n| death_date          = {{Death date and age|2003|10|06|1962|07|10}}\n| death_place  = near Islamabad\n| placeofburial_label = \n| children     = [[Moavia Azam Tariq]]\n| placeofburial_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n| allegiance    = [[Sipah-e-Sahaba Pakistan]] \n| branch        =\n| serviceyears  = \n| rank          = \n| unit          =\n| commands      =\n| battles       =\n| awards        =\n| relations     =\n| laterwork     =\n}}\n\n'''Azam Tariq ''' ([[Urdu]]: '''\u0627\u0639\u0638\u0645 \u0637\u0627\u0631\u0642''' March 1962 \u2013 6 October 2003) was the leader of the politico-religious organisation [[ Sipah-e-Sahaba Pakistan]], a [[Deobandi]]  organization, which was officially banned by the government of [[Pakistan]] in August 2001.On 26 June 2018, Pakistan lifted ban on Sipah-e-Sahaba Pakistan.[https://tribune.com.pk/story/1744294/1-govt-lifts-ban-aswj-unfreezes-assets-chief-ahmed-ludhianvi/]\n\nAfter his death in 2003, [[Muhammad Ahmed Ludhianvi]] was selected as the president of [[Sipah-e-Sahaba Pakistan]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nHe was born to a poor farmer Mohammad Fateh in [[Chichawatni]].<ref name=\"newslinemagazine.com\">http://newslinemagazine.com/magazine/in-death-as-in-life/</ref> He studied at a local madrassa and then enrolled in the Jamia Uloom Islamia in Binori Town, Karachi.<ref name=\"newslinemagazine.com\"/> [[Maulana Moawiyah Azam]] is his elder son, currently active somewhere.\n\n==Career==\nAzam Tariq was elected three times to the [[National Assembly of Pakistan]] in [[Jhang]].<ref>https://www.middle-east-online.com/en/pakistan\u2019s-sunni-shia-rift</ref>\n\nIn August 2001, Pakistani president [[Pervez Musharraf]] banned seven alleged Islamic organizations, including Sipah-e-Sahaba, and Azam Tariq was arrested and jailed on charges of terrorism.\n\n==Assassination==\nAzam Tariq was shot and killed in an attack on October 6, 2003 in a hail of bullets alongside [[Islamabad]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://archive.democrats.com/preview.cfm?term=Pakistan | title = The Hammer Poised to Strike in Pakistan | date = Oct 10, 2003 | website = archive.democrats.com | archive-url = https://archive.today/20051127085005/http://archive.democrats.com/preview.cfm?term=Pakistan | archive-date = November 27, 2005 | url-status = live | access-date = May 8, 2019 }}</ref> as he left the [[M2 motorway (Pakistan)|M2 Motorway]] to enter the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/118945 |title=Azam Tariq gunned down in Islamabad |date=7 October 2003 |access-date=29 June 2018 |website=Dawn.com}}</ref> \n\nThe assassination come after a growing wave of violent incidents in Pakistan between the sectarian Sunni dominance and the smaller community of the Shiah Muslims. Violence peaked up in July with the [[2003 Quetta mosque bombing]] and the massacre of more than 50 people.<ref>{{cite web | author = [[Imtiaz Gul]] | url = https://www.aljazeera.com/archive/2003/10/20084916332362185.html | title = Cleric murder highlights sectarianism | date = Oct 8, 2003 | publisher = [[Aljazeera.com]] | archive-url = https://archive.today/20170424101307/https://www.aljazeera.com/archive/2003/10/20084916332362185.html | archive-date = April 24, 2017 | url-status = live | access-date = May 8, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nOn May 11, 2017, the [[Federal Investigation Agency]] (FIA) arrested a proclaimed offender after 13 years who murdered him.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/1406951/suspect-azam-tariqs-murder-arrested-islamabad-airport/|title=Former ASWJ leader Maulana Azam Tariq's suspected murderer arrested from Islamabad airport |publisher=The Express Tribune |date=11 May 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n===Books by him===\n*''R\u016bd\u0101d-i \u02bbishq o vaf\u0101'', Jhang : Markaz\u012b Daftar-i Sip\u0101h-i \u1e62a\u1e25\u0101bah, 1999-2004, around 1000 pages (in 2 volumes). <small>Author's memoirs.</small>\n*''Ahamm\u012byat-i \u1e25ad\u012bs\u0332 dar d\u012bn'', K\u0101bul : Mayvand ; Peshawar : Kit\u0101bkh\u0101nah-\u02bci Sab\u0101, 2005, 298 p. <small>Importance of [[Hadith]] for Islam, in Persian.</small>\n*''K\u0332h\u0332ut\u0324b\u0101t-i jarnail, al-ma\u02bbr\u016bf, K\u0332h\u0332ut\u0324b\u0101t-i jel'', Jhang : Markaz\u012b Daftar-i Sip\u0101h-i \u1e62a\u1e25\u0101bah, 2001. Collection of speeches written in jail (1998-1999) collected by Ab\u016b Us\u0101mah Z\u0324iy\u0101urra\u1e25m\u0101n N\u0101\u1e63ir.\n\n===Books about him===\n*Mu\u1e25ammad Nad\u012bm Q\u0101sim\u012b, ''\u1e24ay\u0101t-i A\u02bb\u1e93am T\u0324\u0101riq : Mu\u1e25ammad A\u02bb\u1e93am T\u0324\u0101riq ke mufa\u1e63\u1e63il \u1e25\u0101l\u0101t-i zindag\u012b'', Fai\u1e63al\u0101b\u0101d : Ish\u0101\u02bbatulma\u02bb\u0101rif, 1998, 413 p.\n*Mu\u1e25ammad Nad\u012bm Mu\u02bb\u0101viyah, ''P\u0101rl\u012bman\u1e6d k\u0101 shahz\u0101dah : S\u0332\u0101n\u012b-i jarnail-i Sip\u0101h-yi \u1e62a\u1e25\u0101bah ... \u1e24az\u0324rat Maul\u0101n\u0101 Mu\u1e25ammad A\u02bb\u1e93am T\u0324\u0101riq shah\u012bd ke mufa\u1e63\u1e63al \u1e25\u0101l\u0101t-i zindag\u012b aur P\u0101rl\u012bmant k\u012b taq\u0101r\u012br'' Kar\u0101ch\u012b : Maktabah-yi K\u0332h\u0332il\u0101fat-i R\u0101shidah, 2005, 376 p.\n==See also==\n* [[Haq Nawaz Jhangvi]] \n* [[Isar-ul-Haq Qasmi]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.shianews.com/hi/articles/politics/0000116.php Shia News]: a partisan account of Azam Tariq's release in 2001, with a background of the history of Sunni-Shia violence in Pakistan\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070927185726/http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=story_21-3-2004_pg7_28 Pakistan ''Daily Times'' October 7, 2004]\n* [http://www.shianews.com/hi/talking_corner/topic_id/0000015.php Shia News report of Azam Tariq's assassination]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060206231705/http://www.newsline.com.pk/NewsOct2003/stopoct1.htm An Eye for an Eye?] Azam Tariq's assassination news by Newsline (Pakistan).\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tariq, Azam}}\n\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:2003 deaths]]\n[[Category:Pakistani prisoners and detainees]]\n[[Category:Pakistani religious leaders]]\n[[Category:Pakistani MNAs 1990\u20131993]]\n[[Category:Pakistani MNAs 1993\u20131996]]\n[[Category:Pakistani MNAs 2002\u20132007]]\n[[Category:People from Chichawatni]]\n[[Category:Shia\u2013Sunni sectarian violence in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Assassinated Pakistani people]]\n[[Category:Assassinated religious leaders]]\n[[Category:Pakistani far-right politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Arslan-San", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBooks by him", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Azam_Tariq_(religious_leader)"}
{"title_page": "Paul Dooley", "text_new": "{{short description|American actor, writer and comedian|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{for|the Australian rules footballer|Paul Dooley (footballer)}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Paul Dooley\n| image = Paul Dooley.png\n| alt = \n| caption = Dooley in 2010\n| birth_name = Paul Brown \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1928|02|22}}\n| birth_place = [[Parkersburg, West Virginia]], U.S.\n| residence   = [[Toluca Lake, Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| death_place = \n| nationality = \n| other_names = \n| education = \n| alma_mater = [[West Virginia University]]\n| occupation  = {{hlist|Actor|writer|comedian}}\n| years_active =Stage 1950s\u2013<br>Film 1964-present\n| known_for = \n| home_town = \n| spouse = Donna Lee Wasser<br>(m. 1958\u2013?; divorced)<br/>{{marriage|[[Winnie Holzman]]<br>|1984}}\n| children = 4; including [[Savannah Dooley]]\n}}\n\n'''Paul Dooley''' (born '''Paul Brown'''; February 22, 1928) is an American actor, writer and comedian.\n\n== Early life ==\nDooley was born '''Paul Brown''' in [[Parkersburg, West Virginia|Parkersburg]], West Virginia, the son of Ruth Irene (n\u00e9e Barringer), a homemaker, and Peter James Brown, a factory worker.<ref name=\"filmref\">{{cite web|title=Paul Dooley Biography (1928-) |url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/36/Paul-Dooley.html|work=Film Reference|publisher=Advameg, Inc.|accessdate=3 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nHe has said that Parkersburg had few attractions that interested him, as there were not many cultural opportunities. He enjoyed listening to comedians on the radio, especially [[Jimmy Durante]].<ref name=KPCS />\n\nDooley was a [[cartoonist]] as a youth and drew a strip for a local paper in Parkersburg. He joined the [[United States Navy]]. Dooley then returned home and graduated from [[West Virginia University]] in 1952.<ref name=Bio-AandE />\n\n== Career ==\nAfter graduating from West Virginia University, Dooley went to New York City to try his luck in the entertainment industry. He initially found work as a clown for children's birthday parties.<ref name=FilmBug />\n\nIn New York he soon found success as a regular on the stage. In the early 1950s, he made his debut on the New York stage and was discovered by [[Mike Nichols]]. The director gave him his first break by casting him in 1965's ''[[The Odd Couple (play)|The Odd Couple]]'' on Broadway. Dooley played a poker buddy and understudied [[Art Carney]], who played Felix Unger. Eventually when Carney left the play Dooley got the part. He got an agent at [[William Morris Agency]] thanks to a referral from [[Walter Matthau]], who played Oscar Madison in the play.<ref name=Bio-AandE />\n\nAlso having an interest in comedy, Dooley was a [[Stand-up comedy|stand-up comedian]] for five years, eventually landing on ''[[The Tonight Show]],''<ref name=FilmBug /> and a member of the [[Compass Players]] and The Second City troupe in New York City. Fellow members of The Second City at that time were [[Alan Arkin]] and [[Alan Alda]].<ref name=LAWkly-2013>{{cite news |last=Friedlander|first=Whitney|title=Wicked Writer Winnie Holzman and Her Husband Paul Dooley Wrote and Star in a Play Together. It Only Took Them 28 Years |url=http://blogs.laweekly.com/arts/2013/03/winnie_holzman_paul_dooley_cha.php |accessdate=3 January 2014|newspaper=LA Weekly|date=March 29, 2013}}</ref>\n\nDooley also worked as a writer. He created and was one of the head writers on ''[[The Electric Company (1971 TV series)|The Electric Company]],'' produced by the [[Sesame Workshop|Children's Television Workshop]] (now called Sesame Workshop) for [[PBS]] in the United States. Dooley wrote \"runners\", a series of short sketches with 8 or 10 characters that were broadcast over the course of several weeks. He found out years later that [[Carl Reiner]] had recommended him for the job.<ref name=KPCS /> Dooley formed a company with Andrew Duncan and Lynne Lipton called All Over Creation to create commercials for radio and television. They produced around 500 TV commercials and 1,000 radio spots.<ref name=FilmBug /> A character named Paul the Gorilla that appeared in television commercials was named after him.\n\n=== Films ===\nDooley has appeared in such films as ''[[Sixteen Candles]]'', ''[[Popeye (1980 film)|Popeye]]'', ''[[Raggedy Ann and Andy: A Musical Adventure]]'', ''[[Breaking Away]]'', and the voice of [[Sarge (Cars)|Sarge]] in the [[Disney]]/[[Pixar]] films ''[[Cars (film)|Cars]]'', ''[[Cars 2]]'' and ''[[Cars 3]].''\n\nHe worked with [[Robert Altman]] regularly and is known as a prolific journeyman [[character actor]].<ref name=Bio-AandE>{{cite web|title=Paul Dooley|url=http://www.biography.com/people/paul-dooley-224922|work=Bio|publisher=A+E Television Networks, LLC.|accessdate=4 January 2014}}</ref> After Altman saw Dooley in the [[Jules Feiffer]] comedy ''Hold Me'', he signed him for a role in his film ''[[A Wedding]].''<ref name=FilmBug>{{cite web|title=Paul Dooley|url=http://www.filmbug.com/db/256997|work=Film Bug|accessdate=4 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nHe and Altman co-wrote the film [[Health (film)|''Health'']].<ref name=KPCS /> Dooley also wrote ''Easy Reader'' ([[Morgan Freeman]]), ''Fargo North, Decoder'' ([[Skip Hinnant]]), and ''[[Love of Chair]]''.<ref name=KPCS />\n\nHe was also in the director's cut of ''[[Little Shop of Horrors (1986 film)|Little Shop of Horrors]]'', but was replaced by [[Jim Belushi]] in the final cut.\n\nDooley has worked with [[Christopher Guest]] on a number of films.<ref name=FilmBug />\n\n=== Television ===\nDooley has also appeared as a variety of recurrent characters on numerous television shows, including ''[[My So-Called Life]]'', ''[[Dream On (TV series)|Dream On]]'', ''[[Grace Under Fire]]'', ''[[Thirtysomething (TV series)|thirtysomething]]'', ''[[Curb Your Enthusiasm]]'', ''[[ALF (TV series)|ALF]]'' (playing Whizzer Deaver) and ''[[Star Trek: Deep Space Nine]]'' where he played the recurring role of [[List of recurring characters in Star Trek: Deep Space Nine#Tain, Enabran|Enabran Tain]]. He guest starred in other primetime shows like ''[[Bewitched]]'', ''[[The Wonder Years]]'', ''[[Sabrina the Teenage Witch (1996 TV series)|Sabrina, the Teenage Witch]]'', ''[[The Golden Girls]]'', ''[[Hot in Cleveland]]'', and ''[[Desperate Housewives]]''. Dooley starred in the short-lived comedy about a couple living in an [[Arizona]] retirement community, ''[[Coming of Age (1988 TV series)|Coming of Age]]'', opposite veteran actors [[Phyllis Newman]], [[Glynis Johns]] and [[Alan Young]].  In 2000, he was nominated for an [[Emmy Award]] for his role as an [[Eccentricity (behavior)|eccentric]] judge on ''[[The Practice]]''.\n\nIn 2010, Dooley played the part of the head chef at Camp Victory, a fictional fat camp, on the short-lived [[ABC Family]] original series ''[[Huge (TV series)|Huge]],'' which was created and written by his wife and daughter.<ref name=NYT-Huge-2010>{{cite news|last=Hale|first=Mike|title=A Close-Knit Team on a Plus-Size Show |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/20/arts/television/20huge.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|accessdate=4 January 2014|newspaper=New York Times|date=June 18, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014 he appeared in an episode of the NBC series ''[[Parenthood (2010 TV series)|Parenthood]]'' as Rocky, a fellow vet and retiree to [[Craig T. Nelson]]'s [[List of Parenthood characters#Zeek Braverman|Zeek Braverman]].<ref name=HitFix-Parenthood-2014>{{cite web|last=Sepinwall|first=Alan|title=Review: 'Parenthood' - 'Promises': Seeing you, seeing me -- Hank makes a discovery about himself, Sarah has a date and Joel and Julia have another fight|url=http://www.hitfix.com/whats-alan-watching/review-parenthood-promises-seeing-you-seeing-me|work=Hitfix.com|publisher=HitFix, Inc.|accessdate=4 January 2014|date=January 2, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 he appeared in the episode \"22 Steps\" of the ABC series ''[[The Good Doctor (TV series)|The Good Doctor]]'' as Glenn, a 72-year-old man with a failing heart who breaks his pacemaker because he wants to die due to the constant pain he is suffering.\n\n=== Theater ===\nDooley co-wrote the play, ''Assisted Living,'' with his wife Winnie Holzman.<ref name=LAWkly-2013 /> It was their first theatrical collaboration. The play premiered on April 5, 2013.<ref name=Playbill-AL-2013>{{cite web|last=Gans|first=Andrew|title=EXCLUSIVE: Assisted Living, New Play By Wicked's Winnie Holzman and Husband Paul Dooley, Will Debut in April|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/175218-EXCLUSIVE-Assisted-Living-New-Play-By-Wickeds-Winnie-Holzman-and-Husband-Paul-Dooley-Will-Debut-in-April|work=Playbill|accessdate=4 January 2014|date=February 21, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130603090421/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/175218-EXCLUSIVE-Assisted-Living-New-Play-By-Wickeds-Winnie-Holzman-and-Husband-Paul-Dooley-Will-Debut-in-April|archivedate=3 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nDooley has been married to [[Winnie Holzman]], whom he first met at an improv acting class in New York,<ref name=\"LAT-AL-2013\" /> since November 18, 1984.<ref name=LAWkly-2013 /> The couple have a daughter [[Savannah Dooley|Savannah]]<ref name=KPCS>{{cite web|last=Pollak|first=Kevin|title=Episode 96 \u2013 Paul Dooley and Winnie Holzman! |url=http://www.hulu.com/watch/318276|work=Kevin Pollak's Chat Show |accessdate=4 January 2014|date=January 17, 2011}}</ref> and live in [[Toluca Lake]] in [[Los Angeles, California]].<ref name=LAT-AL-2013>{{cite news|last=Ng|first=David|title=Finally a go: A couple finishes writing 'Assisted Living,' at Odyssey Theatre Ensemble, nearly 30 years after its inception.|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2013/apr/10/entertainment/la-et-assisted-living-20130410|accessdate=4 January 2014|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=April 10, 2013}}</ref>\n\nHe was previously married to Donna Lee Wasser on September 19, 1958, but their marriage ended in divorce. He has three children from his first marriage: Robin, Adam, and Peter.<ref name=\"filmref\" /> His sister-in-law still lives in Parkersburg at the Willows Center.\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class = \"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class = \"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1964\n|''The Parisienne and the Prudes''\n| Ted K. Worrie\n|\n|-\n| 1968\n|''[[What's So Bad About Feeling Good?]]'' \n|\n|\n|-\n| 1970\n|''[[The Out-of-Towners (1970 film)|The Out-of-Towners]]''\n| Hotel Clerk - Day\n|\n|-\n| 1972\n|''[[Up the Sandbox]]'' \n| Statue of Liberty Guard\n|\n|-\n| 1974\n|''[[The Gravy Train]]''\n| Doctor\n|\n|-\n| 1974\n|''[[Death Wish (1974 film)|Death Wish]]''\n| Cop at Hospital\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1975\n|''[[Fore Play]]''\n| Salesman\n| \n|-\n| 1977\n|''[[Slap Shot (film)|Slap Shot]]'' \n| Hyannisport Announcer\n| \n|-\n| 1977\n|''[[Raggedy Ann & Andy: A Musical Adventure]]''\n| Gazooks (voice)\n| \n|-\n| 1978\n|''[[A Wedding]]''\n| Snooks Brenner\n| \n|-\n| 1979\n|''[[A Perfect Couple]]''\n| Alex Theodopoulos\n| \n|-\n| 1979\n|''[[Breaking Away]]''\n| Dad\n| \n|-\n| 1979\n|''[[Rich Kids (film)|Rich Kids]]''\n| Simon Peterfreund\n| \n|-\n| 1980\n|''[[Health (film)|Health]]''\n| Dr. Gil Gainey\n| \n|-\n| 1980\n| ''[[Popeye (1980 film)|Popeye]]'' \n| [[J. Wellington Wimpy|Wimpy]]\n| \n|-\n| 1981\n| ''[[Paternity (film)|Paternity]]''\n| Kurt\n| \n|-\n| 1982\n| ''[[Endangered Species (1982 film)|Endangered Species]]''\n| Joe Hiatt\n| \n|-\n| 1982\n| ''[[Kiss Me Goodbye (film)|Kiss Me Goodbye]]''\n| Kendall\n| \n|-\n| 1983\n| ''[[Strange Brew]]''\n| Uncle Claude Elsinore\n| \n|-\n| 1983\n| ''[[Going Berserk]]''\n| Dr. Ted\n| \n|-\n| 1984\n| ''[[Sixteen Candles]]'' \n| Jim Baker\n| \n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[O.C. and Stiggs]]''\n| Randall Schwab\n| \n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[Little Shop of Horrors (film)|Little Shop of Horrors]]''\n| Patrick Martin\n| Director's cut only\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[Monster in the Closet]]''\n| Roy\n| \n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[Big Trouble (1986 film)|Big Trouble]]''\n| Noozel\n| \n|-\n| 1988\n| 